<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. Description of the Country around Lakes Superior and Huron, 1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0018</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">but when they descend, warm and calm weather is generally the Result of the Clymical process<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The Portage River is three leagues from the bottom of the bay and in clear weather is distinguishable from the eastern Shore + the Traverse is allowed to be three leagues and is never safe with either a Southerly or Northerly wind as the first may blow you into the lake and the last sends in a Swell often too heavy for loaded Canoes<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  I have some Reluctance in relating an accident which twice happened to my watch nearly in the middle of this Traverse as it appears to have Something of the marve<span class="AddHand-author">l</span>lous in it<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[H]</span>owever so it was, that in June 1792 I took it from my pocket to see the hour and it became instantly deranged Running down the whole chain in less than a minute<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  I sent it down to Montreal and got it up the ensuing Year and it again played me the Same prank in the Same place<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[N]</span>ow whether this Was merely accident or Owing to some powerful magnetic influence I cannot pretend to say<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The River empties itself into a Small bay and has a large Sand bank some hundred yards from the enterance<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The beach of this bay is Strewed with a great Variety of Stones Ready</p>

